on to exoplanetary science will be in identifying the\nmain constituents of hundreds of exoplanets in various mass/temperature\nregimes, meaning that we will be looking no longer at individual cases but at\npopulations. Such a universal view is critical if we truly want to understand\nthe processes of planet formation and evolution in various environments.\n  In this paper we present a selection of key results. The full results are\navailable online (http://www.ucl.ac.uk/exoplanets/echotargetlist/).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Mar 2014 09:58:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 5 Jan 2015 16:06:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-18"}
{"id":"1403.0358","submitter":"Ivan K. Kostov","authors":"Eldad Bettelheim and Ivan Kostov","title":"Semi-classical analysis of the inner product of Bethe states","comments":"22 pages, 0 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1751-8113/47/24/245401","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the inner product of two Bethe states, one of which is taken\non-shell, in an inhomogeneous XXX chain in the Sutherland limit, where the\nnumber of magnons is comparable with the length L of the chain and the magnon\nrapidities arrange in a small number of macroscopically large Bethe strings.\nThe leading order in the large L limit is known to be expressed through a\ncontour integral of a dilogarithm. Here we derive the subleading term. Our\nanalysis is based on a new contour-integral representation of the inner product\nin terms of a Fredholm determinant. We give two derivations of the sub-leading\nterm. Besides a direct derivation by solving a Riemann-Hilbert problem, we give\na less rigorous, but more intuitive derivation by field-theoretical methods.\nFor that we represent the Fredholm determinant as an expectation value in a\nFock space of chiral fermions and then bosonize. We construct a collective\nfield for the bosonized theory, the short wave-length part of which may be\nevaluated exactly, while the long wave-length part is amenable to a $1/L$\nexpansion. Our treatment thus results in a systematic 1/L expansion of\nstructure factors within the Sutherland limit.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Mar 2014 09:59:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 30 May 2014 08:10:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-18"}
